commitResults.messageBody:
# Conflicts:
#	src/main/java/duke/command/Parser.java
#	src/main/java/duke/storage/Storage.java
#	src/main/java/duke/task/Deadline.java
#	src/main/java/duke/task/TaskList.java
#	src/main/java/duke/ui/Ui.java

Java assertions are added to help identify and catch bugs early in the
development process.

* Task class: Ensure that task type is not null and necessary fields are
  initialized correctly.

* Deadline class: Ensure either LocalDateTime or byString is non-null in
  Deadline creation and handle missing task description.

* Event class: Ensure both start and end times are correctly parsed and
  handle missing task description.

* TaskList class: Ensure correct handling of task addition, deletion,
  and marking status.

* ToDo class: Ensure proper initialization and message generation for
  ToDo tasks.

* Ui class: Ensure appropriate error messages and responses are handled
  in the Ui class.

* Duke class: Ensure correct initialization of storage and task list
  in Duke class.

* Parser class: Ensure response is not null and running status is a
  boolean.

commitResults.messageTitle: Enhancing Code Quality for Improved Readability and Maintainability
commitResults.messageBody:
The code exhibits certain aspects that compromise its readability and
maintainability, and it deviates from Checkstyle guidelines.

To enhance the overall quality of the codebase, improve readability,
and make it align with Checkstyle guidelines for better consistency
and compliance.

* Helper functions are being extracted to condense lengthy methods,
  contributing to improved code organization and readability.
* Magic numbers are being replaced with named constants to enhance code
  clarity and facilitate easier maintenance.
* Guard clauses are being implemented at method entry points to create
  a cleaner and more understandable happy path.
* An enumeration for task status is being introduced to enhance code
  organization and ensure consistent handling of task statuses.

These changes aim to create a codebase that is not only more readable
and maintainable but also aligned with industry best practices and
coding standards.

The task management system lacks a prioritization feature,
limiting users' ability to distinguish and prioritize tasks effectively.

Prioritizing tasks is essential for effective time management and
ensuring that critical tasks are addressed promptly. This feature will
enhance the overall usability of the system.

Introduce a priority tagging system using the "/p" tag, allowing users
to assign low, medium, or high priority to tasks. This empowers users to
organize and manage their tasks based on priority levels.

The "/p" tag provides a clear and intuitive method for users to indicate
the priority of their tasks. This approach is simple, consistent, and
aligns with user expectations.

Additionally, code refactoring has been performed to enhance readability
and comply with checkstyle guidelines. This ensures that the codebase
remains maintainable and follows best practices.
